{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20800"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20800"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.12,0.01,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13675"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13675"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5131"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43952"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for repeat prescriptions. She has been taking esomeprazole for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease for the past three years. She reports her symptoms are well-controlled with no breakthrough heartburn. She has no alarm symptoms such as weight loss, dysphagia, or early satiety. She has a history of hypertension treated with amlodipine. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 27 kg/m2. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trial gradual dose reduction","Continue current dose indefinitely","Change to different proton pump inhibitor","Cease medication immediately","Switch to twice daily dosing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has uncomplicated gastro-oesophageal reflux disease that has been well-controlled on a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) for three years. While PPIs are effective acid-suppressing medications, long-term use should be regularly reviewed due to potential adverse effects including increased risk of \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection, community-acquired pneumonia, osteoporotic fractures, and vitamin B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial gradual dose reduction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan. This can involve halving the dose for 4-8 weeks, then transitioning to on-demand therapy if symptoms remain controlled. If symptoms recur, the lowest effective dose should be used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current dose indefinitely\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it exposes the patient to unnecessary long-term risks when dose reduction may be feasible. Regular review and attempts at stepping down therapy are recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease medication immediately\u003C/strong\u003E may lead to rebound acid hypersecretion and symptom recurrence. A gradual reduction is preferred to allow both patient and stomach adaptation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitch to twice daily dosing\u003C/strong\u003E would increase medication exposure unnecessarily in a patient whose symptoms are well-controlled on current dosing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to different proton pump inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the core issue of long-term PPI use and would not provide any additional benefit in this case. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long-term proton pump inhibitor therapy should be regularly reviewed with attempts at dose reduction or cessation.","Step-down strategies include reducing to lowest effective dose, switching to on-demand therapy, or transitioning to H2-receptor antagonists.","Prolonged PPI use is associated with increased risks of C. difficile infection, pneumonia, fractures, and vitamin B12 deficiency."],"references":["Choosing wisely [Internet]. [cited 2025 Mar 30]. Don\u2019t use proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) long term in patients with uncomplicated disease without regular attempts at reducing dose or ceasing. Available from: https://www.choosingwisely.org.au/recommendations/racgp1","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Gastrointestinal. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [Internet]. Version 17. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 [cited 2025 Mar 30]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20800"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90308"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T13:33:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T13:47:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13675"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","